<HEADLINE>
FT  08 OCT 94 / Treuhand to seek more cuts in steel output
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Germany's Treuhand privatisation agency is likely to push for further cuts
in steel capacity in eastern Germany in a bid to persuade the European
Commission to accept the sale of Eko Stahl, the last of the East German
steel mills, to Cockerill-Sambre, the Belgian steel producers.
Mr Hans Schwarz, head of the workers' council at the Hennigsdorf steel mill
in the eastern state of Brandenburg, said the agency might buy back a part
of the mill in order to close down one of the hot-rolling complexes which is
under-utilised.
Hennigsdorf, which is owned by Riva, the Italian privately-owned steel
group, produces about 700,000 tonnes of steel a year, but its capacity could
increase to 1m tonnes when its hot-rolling operation is complete.
The agency's policy could have the affect of keeping overall capacity levels
in eastern Germany down if Cockerill buys Eko Stahl, but could also mean
further job losses in the industry.
Under the terms of the European Union steel levels agreement, Eko Stahl must
not produce more than 900,000 tonnes until 1999, when production can then
rise. Mr Scharwz said the 850-strong work force at Hennigsdorf would be
reduced by nearly a sixth if the plans went ahead.
</TEXT>
