<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 94 / Row looms over Pounds 1.3bn French aid proposal for Bull
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER and JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS, PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A fresh storm over the use of government aid to prop up ailing European
companies is likely next week.
Mr Karel Van Miert, European competition commissioner, is expected to
recommend approval of payments totalling FFr11bn (Pounds 1.32bn) from the
French government to Groupe Bull, the loss-making computer group.
This will heighten tension between the Commission and private European
enterprise amid growing criticism that Brussels is not doing enough to stop
governments distorting competition through state-funded rescue plans.
This week the UK government and seven European airlines appealed to the
European Court of Justice to annul the Commission's decision to allow the
French government to grant FFr20bn in fresh subsidies to Air France, the
national carrier.
The Commission told the French government earlier this year to suspend a
capital injection of FFr2.5bn for Bull pledged in February 1993 by a
previous administration. At the end of last year, the centre-right
government of Mr Edouard Balladur announced a new capitalisation plan of
FFr8.6bn of which FFr1.6bn would come from France Telecom, a shareholder in
Bull.
Mr Van Miert's recommendation is likely to go before his fellow
commissioners for approval next week. With only a majority of votes required
for authorisation, it is almost certain the French government will win the
go-ahead for the capital injection.
The Commission is likely to attach conditions to the granting of aid, which
will probably stipulate that Groupe Bull stick to its own restructuring
proposals and receive no more aid during the restructuring.
The French government claims the capital injections are a vital element in a
package aimed at restoring the group to profitability after accumulated
losses of about FFr20bn since 1989. Mr Gerard Longuet, the industry
minister, has described the capital injections as a 'one time-last time'
injection before the privatisation of the group.
The restructuring package, implemented by Mr Jean-Marie Descarpentries, who
took over as chairman of the computer group last year, involves a sharp cut
in overhead costs, the sale of assets, and the reduction of the company's
Paris sites from 24 to two. An existing plan to cut 6,500 jobs in 1993 and
this year has been accelerated.
According to Bull, the restructuring has helped to cut losses in the first
half of the year to June were reduced to FFr843m, compared with FFr1.98bn
for the comparable period in 1993.
</TEXT>
