<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER ASPDEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The relationship between Frasier Crane and his hapless brother Nyles, laden
with psycho-drama even in its most banal exchanges, also happens to provide
the funniest half-hour on television. This week's Frasier (Channel 4, 10.00)
is the last in the current series: the two siblings meet over a coffee and
wonder if they are really happy. Why is it that only American sitcoms manage
to tap the comedy inherent in all great philosophical questions?
Sue Cook explores the world of the paranormal in Out of This World (BBC1,
9.30), a collection of reconstructed case histories considered by a studio
audience. Among the strange-but-perhaps-true tales is the story of the Hull
housewife who foresaw the Marchioness riverboat disaster, an assassination
attempt on the Pope and a woman who recalls the details of a 16th century
murder.
Chlorine capers aplenty when Burt Lancaster plays a middle-aged man who
suddenly appears beside a swimming pool, and decides to swim home to
Connecticut via the pools of his friends in Frank Perry's diverting 1968
cult movie The Swimmer (Channel 4, 11.10).
</TEXT>
