FT  07 OCT 94 / The Labour Party in Blackpool: Leaders shrug off defence
defeat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Tony Blair suffered his first defeat when the conference yesterday
endorsed earlier demands for the scrapping of the Trident nuclear submarine
force, Ivor Owen writes.
Constituency activists roared approval when it was announced that a card
vote had resulted in a motion condemning Trident being carried by 54.2 per
cent to 45.8 per cent.
It also called for Britain's defence expenditure to be reduced to the
average of other countries in western Europe.
Labour leaders shrugged off the defeat as a ritualistic gesture which would
not change existing policy.
A party spokesman said: 'Historically, Labour conferences have passed
motions on defence facing in different directions.'
He stressed that on Wednesday the conference approved a statement on defence
policy by the national executive committee which reflected the views of Mr
Blair.
