FT  07 OCT 94 / The Labour Party in Blackpool: Nurses pay body rulings to be
adopted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN and JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr David Blunkett, the shadow health secretary, promised a Labour government
would increase nurses' salaries in line with the recommendations made by
their pay review body.
All the pay review bodies for National Health Service employees would be
free to make their own decisions, and the workers would get the increases
they deserved. To cheers, Mr Blunkett said: 'That is our pledge.'
Confirming that the internal market created by the present government would
be replaced with co-operation, he said this would ensure that hospitals once
again put the needs of patients first.
The 'unaccountable' self-governing NHS trusts would be abolished and
existing arrangements under which family doctors could opt to control their
own budgets replaced.
Mr Blunkett said all those involved in the primary care sector would be able
to participate in prioritising and planning as part of a 'joint
commissioning' process.
He confirmed that tobacco advertising would be banned and compulsory
competitive tendering ended.
Delegates approved a resolution which pressed for the strengthening of laws
on the licensing of medicines, and for pharmaceutical companies to be made
more accountable for their products.
Department of Health officials immediately attacked Mr Blunkett's call to
abolish NHS trusts, saying that Labour was 'deeply wedded to the old and
failed command and control doctrines'.
