<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 94 / The Labour Party in Blackpool: Businesses giving delegates
the Tory treatment - Exhibition space for the 1995 Brighton conference is
almost sold out, says Roland Rudd, with companies flocking to woo Labour
supporters
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If you are a company director sufficiently impressed by Mr Tony Blair's new
modern Labour party to want to take an exhibition stall at next year's
Labour conference you had better hurry. Most of the stands for 1995 are sold
out.
More businesses advertised at this year's Labour conference in Blackpool
than ever before. So the party's corporate affairs team raised the minimum
price from Pounds 2,500 to almost Pounds 3,000 and by Tuesday morning had
sold more than 90 per cent of available space for next year's conference in
Brighton.
Business is taking Labour seriously. And Labour is taking the business of
making money equally seriously.
Never mind that Mr Frank Dobson, transport spokesman, when speaking to the
conference likened Mr Bob Horton, chairman of Railtrack, to the fat
controller in Thomas the Tank Engine and said he was not up to his job. That
was just politics - Mr Dobson was telling the delegates what they wanted to
hear.
Neither side took offence. Railtrack has just booked one of the biggest
exhibition stands for next year. The company, which wants to be privatised
quickly, is keen to get its message over to as many Labour people as
possible. Ms Lorraine Satchell, Labour's exhibitions organiser, is delighted
to take its money.
Most delegates taking part in the party's transport debate spoke out against
the break-up and privatisation of British Rail. That did not deter Regional
Railways, created as a prelude to privatisation, from taking an exhibition
stand at Labour's conference.
Mr Steve Hutchinson, the company's advertising account manager, said:
'Irrespective of people's views of privatisation we wanted to position
ourselves as a well-run company.'
The same is true of Nuclear Electric, which took a double stand. Its
management has publicly asked to be privatised but decided to advertise at
the conference in spite of Labour hostility to privatisation.
Even the management of National Power and PowerGen, the electricity
generators criticised by Labour for directors' big salaries and share
options, were discretely wining and dining selected MPs in Blackpool hotels.
Some big companies have decided to advertise their businesses at a Labour
conference for the first time. Sainsbury and Tesco, the food retailers, took
prime stands and have already booked stalls for next year.
Mr Nigel Matthew, Sainsbury's group secretary, said the company had become
more aware of the importance of communicating to the big political parties.
'With Labour controlling so many more local authorities we have to be more
accessible to the party,' he said.
Mr Bernard Hughes, Tesco's corporate affairs manager, said his company
wanted to start a dialogue with Labour councillors.
The food retailers are particularly critical of the Department of the
Environment's decision to withhold future planning permission for
out-of-town supermarkets and are keen to tell Labour how many jobs will be
created from their continued expansion into the green belt.
As one food retailing manager said: 'Let's face it, with Labour likely to
form the next government its become more important than ever to talk to
Labour politicians.'
British Airways has long booked space at Labour conferences. This year it
took to advertising its club-class seats. 'This is a party full of
aspiration, so why shouldn't we be telling them about our new club-class
seats?' asked a BA spokesman.
If wanting to be treated the same as a well-heeled Tory counts as aspiration
then BA has a point.
Mr David Clark, the party's defence spokesman, last year led a revolt
against BA serving ordinary white wine at its Labour conference reception
when he discovered that the airline was offering champagne to the Tories.
Sir Colin Marshall, BA's chairman, quickly got the point, and this year made
sure Labour MPs were offered the company's own blend of Piper Heidsieck
champagne reserved for first-class passengers.
</TEXT>
