<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 94 / The Labour Party in Blackpool: Brown denies planning for
sterling crisis
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Gordon Brown, the shadow chancellor, yesterday rejected suggestions in a
newspaper that he had started to plan for a sterling crisis after the next
general election.
In an interview with Tribune, a leftwing Labour weekly, Mr Brown was quoted
as saying that he was seeking agreements with the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund in advance of the general election.
The report raised the spectre of international intervention along the lines
of the 1976 economic crisis when the then Mr Denis Healey, Labour
chancellor, was forced to call on IMF help to restore currency stability.
However, Labour officials said Mr Brown's comments had been misinterpreted.
They said he was referring to the general problem of financial market
instability, and insisted that there was 'no question' of plans for an IMF
rescue package.
The Tribune article refers to the pressure on sterling that greeted the 1929
and 1964 Labour governments, and says that Mr Brown was asked 'about the
inevitable run on the pound'.
Mr Brown is quited as replying: 'We are already working on plans to tackle
the problem, should it arise. We are under no illusions.
'But we are seeking . . . new international agreements through the World
Bank and the IMF. We are doing this in advance of the next election through
our various contacts.'
Mr Brown was then asked: 'Are you saying that the speculators and the modern
gnomes of Zurich can be checked?' He responded: 'Yes, I believe they can. I
believe it can be made much more difficult for the international speculators
and gamblers.' He added: 'I really do believe we can ride that threat.'
Mr Brown's aides said he had been quoted accurately. But they said that the
possibility of a sterling crisis following the election of a Labour
government had never been put to him.
An adviser said: 'What he was asked was: 'Are you worried about the problem
of instability and speculation in financial markets, and could this be a
problem for a Labour government?''
Mr Brown, who raised the prospect of greater international co-ordination in
his conference speech on Monday, will travel to Washington next week for
talks with US officials which will include discussions on market
instability.
</TEXT>
