<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 94 / MPs to demand shake-up at CSA
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A powerful committee of MPs looks set to recommend sweeping changes to the
controversial Child Support Agency in a move that would increase pressure on
the government to implement new reforms.
An early draft of the social security committee's latest report, circulated
this week to committee members, is understood to argue for changes in many
areas. These include the formula used when setting the level of maintenance
payments to be made by absentee fathers and so-called 'clean break'
settlements between divorced couples.
The draft also makes radical proposals for involving the committee in the
process of assessing any new CSA-related legislation put forward by
ministers, whether primary or secondary, before it is enacted.
If the suggestions in this area are adopted, they could set an important
precedent for the way bills are scrutinised by MPs on their passage through
parliament.
Members of the committee, which has a Conservative majority, will meet to
discuss the draft on October 19, after MPs return from the summer recess.
The final report is expected to appear by November, just in time to
influence government thinking about whether to include a CSA reform bill in
the Queen's Speech.
This is under active consideration by ministers, although the government
will probably wish to avoid primary legislation on such a controversial
topic if it can.
Ministers are keen either to be in step with the committee's recommendations
or to have convincing arguments ready to deal with the points where they are
not.
Most recommendations in the committee's first report on the CSA, published
last year, were implemented.
The draft is thought to advocate simplifying the maintenance-payment formula
along the lines of current practice in Australia and New Zealand, and to
suggest allowing assessment levels to be reduced in some cases of
'clean-break' settlements.
The current principle is that these settlements cannot be offset against
maintenance payments.
In an article published last month, Mr Frank Field, the committee's Labour
chairman, came out in favour of lower payments for parents who started
second families 'on the basis that taxpayers will look after first families'
than those who 'act knowing the CSA is in existence and here to stay'.
The draft urges better co-ordination between the CSA and the Benefits Agency
and suggests that consideration be given to the introduction of maintenance
'disregards'.
It discusses the possible introduction some form of appeals system - a move
Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, cautioned against in the Commons
earlier this year.
The draft proposes that the Commons committee be asked to hold public
hearings on new CSA-related primary legislation after the bill's second
reading but before it enters standing committee. It says the committee
should be asked to hold similar hearings into any new statutory instruments
soon after they are published.
</TEXT>
