<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 94 / Minister pledges help for Tyneside
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Extra measures to help rejuvenate Tyneside in the wake of a wave of recent
heavy job losses were pledged yesterday by Mr Ian Taylor, trade and
technology minister.
He announced during a visit to Newcastle upon Tyne that the government had
given the Tyne and Wear Development Corporation approval to spend Pounds
8.7m on redeveloping part of South Shields' riverside.
The Northern Development Company would be given an additional Pounds 50,000
to promote inward investment opportunities and redundant employees would be
given immediate access to Tyneside Training and Enterprise Council courses
and Employment Service programmes.
Mr Taylor confirmed the government's support, first voiced 17 months ago,
for a Tyneside enterprise zone, subject to European Commission approval, if
local people favoured it. This, he said, could benefit the region to the
tune of Pounds 40m and create a possible 5,000 jobs.
He said the government was considering proposals from the private and public
sectors to help Tyneside build on its maritime skills by moving into sub-sea
technology.
