<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 94 / Linkmen to paramilitaries play down hopes of loyalist
ceasefire: Stewart Dalby cautions against premature expectations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Intense speculation in Belfast that Ulster's loyalist paramilitaries will
announce their expected ceasefire within two weeks appears to be
over-optimistic.
Mr David Ervine of the Progressive Unionist Party, who is described as
having an insight into loyalist paramilitary thinking, said: 'I am confident
there will be a ceasefire. But the speculation that it will happen within
the next two weeks is unrealistic.'
The Rev Roy Magee, who is also ascribed an insight into paramilitary
thinking, agreed . He certainly speaks to the unnamed shadowy loyalist
paramilitary leaders, if not for them. Asked whether he thought there would
be a loyalist ceasefire, he said: 'Yes, but I am not sure it is imminent.
'I have been saying all along that the paramilitaries must be given time to
consult everybody. After all, it has taken nearly nine months since the
Downing Street declaration for the IRA leadership to get everyone on board.
The Protestant leaders must be given time.'
The loyalist groups made four conditions for a ceasefire:
A cessation of violence by the republican splinter group the Irish National
Liberation Army.
Evidence that the IRA ceasefire is permanent.
Conviction that there was no secret deal with the IRA.
An assurance that nothing in the framework document being drafted by the
London and Dublin governments would weaken the union with Britain.
The paramilitaries, like some of the constitutional unionists, believe that
Mr John Major, the prime minister, did not make a secret deal with the IRA.
The INLA is thought not to have the wherewithal to go against the wishes of
the bigger Provisional IRA, whose ceasefire looks more solid every day.
The sticking point is thus the framework document, being drawn up by the two
governments to lay the basis for discussion about possible cross-border
arrangements.
A problem here is that the framework document keeps disappearing over the
horizon. It was to have appeared in September, then by the end of October.
Now it seems it will not be ready until November.
Mr Ervine suggested an actual sighting of the document may not be entirely
necessary to calm loyalist fears. An assurance by the governments that the
framework document was a discussion document and not a rigid agenda might do
the trick, he said.
Mr Magee said any ceasefire would mirror that of the IRA - it would not be
declared permanent or involve handing over the considerable arsenal of
weapons the Protestant paramilitaries have been augmenting recently. As with
the IRA, a return to violence at some future date would remain on the cards.
In the past the unionist community has shown a remarkable ability to cohere
and co-ordinate resistance when it felt really threatened.
This cohesion may no longer be possible because, according to Mr Magee, the
paramilitaries have made it clear they will no longer be at the beck and
call of the constituency politicians. 'They feel they have been let down in
the past by the politicians.'
Mr Jim Rodgers, a Belfast councillor for the Ulster Unionist Party and
another man with an insight into paramilitary thinking, said that the
Protestant paramilitaries used to be regarded as less efficient than the IRA
but this has changed.
The Combined Loyalist Military Command embraces and speaks for the main
paramilitary groups - the Ulster Defence Association, which has subsumed the
Ulster Freedom Fighters, and the separate Ulster Volunteer Force.
Mr Rodgers said there were 10,000 men under arms in the joint UDA/UFF and
about 2,500 in the UVF. Others said there were about 4,000 in the UDA and
1,500 in the UVF.
Mr Magee estimated there were about 1,000 active Protestant paramilitaries.
But more important than numbers was the increasing sophistication of the
Protestants. The army confirmed that they had developed bomb-making
abilities and they also had better arms.
Mr Magee believed that in order to avoid conflict with the largely
Protestant British army or the RUC and Royal Irish Regiment, they would
target places in the Republic. The violence would therefore move south.
</TEXT>
<XX>
