<DATE>941007
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 94 / Vatman swoops on canned cuppa
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIM KELLY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Customs and Excise has decided to tax drinks which are called tea but are
not freshly brewed.
The department has ruled that 'iced tea', sold in bottles or cans and
sometimes artificially flavoured, is a soft drink and should carry value
added tax at the standard rate.
Tax experts came to the decision yesterday after coming up with a definition
of tea which it thought would be accepted by 'the ordinary man in the
street'.
Customs said: 'Applying this criteria to tea the commissioners consider tea
as a drink made by pouring hot water on leaves, leaving it for a few minutes
to infuse, that is drunk, either hot or cold, to refresh and quench the
thirst.'
It added: 'In our view the ordinary man in the street would see a packaged
ice tea product as similar to a soft drink and not as a substitute for the
ordinary tea that the majority of the population drinks.'
Customs ruled that zero exemption should not extend to preparations which
include fruit juice or flavouring and citric acid, and which compete with
other beverages in the soft drink market.
Mr Carl Short, food manufacturing analyst with SGST Securities, said: 'Iced
tea has been a fast-growing market in the US during recent years and could
produce some excitement in the UK's tea and soft drinks markets. It
bestrides both the fast-growing soft drinks sector and the more mature tea
market.'
Herbal teas and similar products will continue to be zero rated for VAT
because they are considered to be ordinary foodstuffs which are drunk
instead of tea, or as an alternative.
A spokesman said that the concept of 'iced-tea' was a misnomer and the
department was always vigilant when new products started to appear on the
market. Iced tea served in a cafe or restaurant would not carry VAT as it
was brewed with real tea.
Customs made their decision in the light of past judgments of the
independent VAT tribunals which consider appeals by manufacturers. An appeal
may be made to yesterday's ruling.
</TEXT>
<XX>
