<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 94 / Littlechild favours sell-off of nuclear power industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Professor Stephen Littlechild, the electricity regulator, favours
privatising the nuclear power industry, but believes power stations should
be redistributed among the two state-owned companies, Nuclear Electric and
Scottish Nuclear, in order to improve competition.
Prof Littlechild says in his submission to the government's nuclear review:
'There would be benefits in ensuring that all market participants throughout
Britain are fully exposed to private-sector financial disciplines. This
would maintain continuing pressure for increased efficiency.'
Prof Littlechild expresses two concerns, however. One is that all financial
aid should be removed from nuclear power. At the moment both companies are
subsidised either by electricity consumers or the taxpayer, and this is
creating market distortions.
The second is that the two companies each have strong market positions which
could inhibit competition. Prof Littlechild proposes that the bigger
company, Nuclear Electric, hand a number of power stations to Scottish
Nuclear. This would weaken Nuclear Electric's market position in England and
Wales and strengthen Scottish Nuclear's position south of the border.
Alternatively, Scottish Nuclear could give one of its power stations to
Nuclear Electric so as to introduce a new competitor into the Scottish
market.
Prof Littlechild says there is no case for the government subsidising the
construction of further nuclear plant because it is not needed.
Both companies welcomed the regulator's support for privatisation but
reacted coolly to his proposals for plant reallocation.
The government should assist the construction of further nuclear capacity to
ensure diversity of supply and keep alive the UK's nuclear technology
capability, says the Institution of Electrical Engineers.
The body says in its submission to the review that the future of fossil
fuels is uncertain and only nuclear can fill the gap. Nuclear also provides
environmental advantages because it produces no gaseous emissions.
</TEXT>
