<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 94 / Farmers fear loss of subsidies in expanded EU
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON MAITLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Farmers face the abolition of all price support if eastern European
countries join the European Union, the National Farmers' Union said
yesterday.
This prospect was set out in a paper drawn up by the union's leadership and
launched at a meeting of its policy-making council.
Mr Martin Haworth, head of international affairs, said extending Common
Agricultural Policy subsidies to eastern Europe 'could prove potentially
fatal to the EU'.
Not only would it mean a possible doubling of the present CAP budget of
about Ecu35bn (Pounds 27bn), it would also encourage increased production in
eastern Europe, which has great agricultural potential, and lead to fresh
surpluses in western Europe.
Export of these surpluses to world markets could not be subsidised because
of new limits under the Gatt trade deal.
Mr Haworth said that opposing enlargement of the European Union was
unrealistic since member states were committed to the goal of membership for
six eastern and central European countries - Hungary, Poland, the Czech
Republic, Slovakia, Bulgaria and Romania.
He said: 'There's not much of a choice at all. It's very hard to see how you
can continue with any kind of price support in an enlarged community.'
The document, with one released in March on the implications for the CAP of
the Gatt accord, is very different in tone from the complacent approach
taken by the union in the past.
It follows closely an independent study published, but not endorsed, by the
European Commission, which called for farm subsidies to be phased into
national budgets, with compensation for the worst hit regions.
The union leadership is focusing on two options for reform which it
considers the most realistic.
Eastern European countries could establish a low level of price support for
their farmers - enough to cover essential production costs - in advance of
joining the EU.
Prices for western European farmers would then be lowered to these levels,
with 'some form of further compensation,' according to the paper.
Alternatively, all price support would end, to be replaced with 'decoupled'
aid for EU farmers - payments unrelated to how much they produce. While this
would discourage overproduction, it would have some disadvantages.
The document says: 'They relate to the budgetary cost if an equivalent level
of support is to be granted, or the impact on farm incomes if it is not.'
Mr Haworth accepted that the union's 100,000 members might take a different
view. But he disputed the argument of some farmers that further reforms to
the CAP could be postponed.
He said: 'We need to take a decision as to how we change the CAP very
quickly.
'The more it's delayed, the more these countries will try to align
themselves with the current CAP. This is storing up many more problems than
we've already got.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
</CN>
