<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 94 / Visa cuts fraud losses by 24%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Visa, the international card payments system, said yesterday that fraudulent
payments had fallen by 24 per cent in the first quarter of this year,
reflecting greatly improved detection procedures.
The fall occurred in Visa's Europe, Middle East and Africa division where
sales volume for the first quarter of this year was Dollars 44.6bn, (Pounds
28.2bn) an increase of 11.7 per cent from the first quarter of last year.
Visa defines fraud as the use of lost and stolen cards or cards not received
by the owner, fraudulent applications, counterfeit cards and fraudulent use
of account numbers.
It said that, while the number of attempts to acquire merchandise
fraudulently through the use of its cards had not declined, its use of
technology and 'human intervention programmes' had greatly improved
detection.
Among these is a risk-identification service which identifies suspect
merchants and informs member banks for subsequent action.
A code has been embedded in each card's magnetic strip, which is checked
when it is passed through a point-of-sale terminal. This has helped reduce
counterfeiting or alteration of the magnetic strip and helped reduce losses
through counterfeiting to Dollars 17.5m.
Visa has improved its database so that high-risk areas can be identified and
fraud detection resources allocated to them.
</TEXT>
