<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 94 / Doctors ready to combat local pay
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Doctors' leaders yesterday started preparing plans for action if the
government imposes local pay bargaining on National Health Service
hospitals.
In a move that takes the medical profession a step closer to all-out
confrontation with the government, the British Medical Association decided
to convene its sanctions working party to consider action to be taken if
ministers introduce the proposed pay changes without agreement.
The government intends to start replacing the NHS's centralised pay
structure with local performance-related arrangements next year. It faces
opposition from unions and professional organisations. Hospital doctors are
particularly concerned that they might come under local management pressure
to follow financial rather than clinical priorities.
Mr James Johnson, a Liverpool surgeon who became chairman of the BMA's
central consultants and specialists committee yesterday, said his priority
would be to 'carry on the fight against the government's ill-conceived
proposals'.
The Department of Health has been trying to negotiate BMA agreement on an
enabling clause which would open the way to the shift from centralised to
local pay bargaining. The BMA is refusing to accept the clause, but
ministers have powers to impose it. Mr Johnson said that, if the government
decided to do so, it would give rise to a dispute. The decision to convene
the sanctions working party was in response to calls for action from
consultants who felt 'beleaguered under the government's continuing
onslaught on their professional values'.
The ultimate sanction available to consultants would be mass withdrawal from
the NHS. Some doctors favour setting up consultants' chambers on similar
lines to barristers, enabling them to set the terms on which they would
provide their services to the NHS.
Other consultants fear such a course of action could precipitate the very
thing the BMA is most worried about - the break-up of a health service with
national standards and conditions. More traditional sanctions would include
a decision by consultants to undertake only medical duties, withdrawing from
management tasks and other work not directly related to patient care.
</TEXT>
