<HEADLINE>
FT  07 OCT 94 / Ucatt ballot
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Ucatt, the construction union, has delayed a ballot on its merger with the
TGWU general union until it has completed its financial survival plan.
The union hopes to cut a quarter of its 120 staff in the next few weeks
through the use of voluntary redundancies. It also hopes to sell off four of
its 12 regional offices in an attempt to restore its financial balance by
the end of next year.
The union had a Pounds 1.05m operating deficit last year and has an
accumulated deficit in its general fund of Pounds 3.17m. It had to pay
Pounds 200,000 in interest charges on its Pounds 1.248m overdraft facility
with Unity Bank last year. The bank has insisted that the union must carry
out drastic cuts for continuing financial support.
Mr George Brumwell, Ucatt's general secretary, said yesterday: 'We have
embarked on a final phase of restructuring and rationalisation. That process
is nearing its completion but the union has undergone a major, though very
necessary, upheaval.' He added that the union wanted to see its 'new
regional structure bedded in before tackling the major administrative task
of a full national ballot on merger'.
The union said last night that the merger ballot might go ahead in December
but denied that its postponement from this month by the union's executive's
was due to concerns in the TGWU about the state of the Ucatt's finances.
Ucatt was originally to have an autonomous trade group of the larger union
at the start of 1995, if the ballot had approved the merger.
</TEXT>
