<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 94 / Membership of teacher quango announced
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Teacher Training Agency, the newly formed quango, will aim to fund
institutions according to their quality, Mrs Gillian Shephard, the education
secretary, said yesterday.
She named the membership of the agency, established two weeks ago to fund
teacher training both in English schools, where the government is trying to
introduce new training courses, and in universities.
They include representatives of universities, primary schools and
grant-maintained schools, and members of two other educational quangos - the
School Curriculum and Assessment Authority and the Higher Education Funding
Council for England. The agency hopes to appoint a chief executive by the
end of this month.
The move angered teachers' unions, which had fiercely contested the
legislation which created the agency.
Mrs Shephard said: 'I shall expect the agency to base the distribution of an
increasing proportion of its funding on the grounds of quality and
cost-effectiveness, while developing and maintaining a diverse system of
training.'
She added that the agency should make it a condition of making certain
grants that Ofsted, the schools inspectorate, had full access to assess
quality of provision, while it should also consider assessments by the
higher education funding and quality councils.
Mrs Shephard has the power to require the agency to take account of other
quality measures at a later date.
Mr Doug McAvoy, general secretary of the National Union of Teachers, was
'very fearful' of the new body. He said: 'We've always been anxious about
bodies of this kind when the government appoints the kind of people who will
do that which the government wants. For this body, it has been even more
sinister than usual in the sense that they've kept secret the personnel
until now.'
He attacked the fact that Mrs Shephard had the power to change its terms of
reference.
</TEXT>
