<HEADLINE>
FT  06 OCT 94 / Hewden Stuart chief takes a swipe at City short-termists
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The chairman of Hewden Stuart, the UK's biggest independent plant hire
company, took a swipe at the City yesterday when the group reported interim
profits well above expectations.
Sir Matthew Goodwin, former deputy chairman of the Scottish Conservatives,
blamed short-termist pressure from the City for the failure of many British
companies to maintain investment through the last recession.
He attributed the sharp rebound in the Glasgow-based group's profits to
heavy investment in new plant - worth more than Pounds 100m in the last 18
months.
Hewden Stuart reported a 77 per cent increase in half-year profits to Pounds
16.2m - about 20 per cent ahead of City expectations. Sir Matthew said
trading was continuing at a high level and told analysts: 'You ain't seen
anything yet.'
Sir Matthew, 65, a chartered accountant who has been chairman since 1979,
said he 'did not give a damn' when the group's pre-tax profits collapsed to
Pounds 12m in 1992, compared with Pounds 36m in 1989, at the peak of the
boom. Cash flow, the most important element in evaluating a company, had
remained strong and the company continued to invest in spite of the
downturn.
Known for its cautious approach, the group decided to increase capital
expenditure sharply in July 1993, when it became convinced that recovery was
definitely on the way. It secured good terms from manufacturers, such as a
Belgian supplier of compressors which was about to put its workforce on a
three-day week.
Sir Matthew said the group had continued to invest, even although doing so
depressed immediate profitability.
He said it was 'a tragedy' that so few companies had maintained investment
during the recession and blamed the City's constant demand for short-term
performance. He noted that British Steel had recently warned that supplies
of steel were already tightening. He said: 'Coming from Scotland, you have
to wonder whether we should ever have shut Ravenscraig. We also see
shortages of bricks, because so many kilns have been closed.'
Sir Matthew did not conceal his pleasure at exceeding the analysts'
forecasts. He said Hewden Stuart had decided not to try to upgrade
expectations, since such guidance gave an unfair advantage to institutions
and 'was tantamount to insider dealing'.
Details, Page 24
</TEXT>
